06813nam a22008055i 9780812298253DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122982537 a10.9783/97808122982532doi  a(DE-B1597)590450  a(OCoLC)1296428813  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aDS115.95b.F76 2022 7aHIS0220002bisacsh04a909/.0492422300aFrontiers of Jewish Scholarship :bExpanding Origins, Transcending Borders /ced. by Michael A. Meyer, Anne O. Albert, Noah S. Gerber. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJewish Culture and Contexts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. NEW LANDS -- tChapter 1. Between Past and Future -- tChapter 2. German Wissenschaft des Judentums and the Late Nineteenth-Century Development of Hungarian Jewish Studies -- tChapter 3. Wissenschaft des Judentums Exported to America -- tChapter 4. Forging a New “Empire of Knowledge” -- tPART II. NEW THEMES -- tChapter 5. Between Assonance and Assimilation -- tChapter 6. Christian Contributions to Jewish Scholarship in Italy -- tChapter 7. Integrating National Consciousness into the Study of Jewish History -- tChapter 8. South Asian Frameworks for European Good Intentions -- tChapter 9. Saul Lieberman and Yemenite Jewry -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe birth of modern Jewish studies can be traced to the nineteenth-century emergence of the Wissenschaft des Judentums, a movement to promote a scholarly approach to the study of Judaism and Jewish culture. Frontiers of Jewish Scholarship offers a collection of essays examining how Wissenschaft extended beyond its original German intellectual contexts and was transformed into a diverse, global field. From the early expansion of the new scholarly approaches into Jewish publications across Europe to their translation and reinterpretation in the twentieth century, the studies included here collectively trace a path through largely neglected subject matter, newly recognized as deserving attention.Beginning with an introduction that surveys the field's German origins, fortunes, and contexts, the volume goes on to document dimensions of the growth of Wissenschaft des Judentums elsewhere in Europe and throughout the world. Some of the contributions turn to literary and semantic issues, while others reveal the penetration of Jewish studies into new national contexts that include Hungary, Italy, and even India. Individual essays explore how the United States, along with Israel, emerged as a main center for Jewish historical scholarship and how critical Jewish scholarship began to accommodate Zionist ideology originating in Eastern Europe and eventually Marxist ideology, primarily in the Soviet Union. Finally, the focus of the volume moves on to the land of Israel, focusing on the reception of Orientalism and Jewish scholarly contacts with Yemenite and native Muslim intellectuals.Taken together, the contributors to the volume offer new material and fresh approaches that rethink the relationship of Jewish studies to the larger enterprise of critical scholarship while highlighting its relevance to the history of humanistic inquiry worldwide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJewish learning and scholarshipxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewish learning and scholarshipxHistoryy20th century. 0aWissenschaft des Judentums (Movement). 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aJewish Studies.  aReligion.1 aAlbert, Anne O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlbert, Anne O., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.g